-- Japan, China, India, Malaysia, South Korea: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview
-- Anil Varma
-- 2010-06-17T22:22:23Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-17/japan-china-india-malaysia-south-korea-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: The Bank of Japan will release minutes of its May
monetary policy meeting at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo. Chief Cabinet
Secretary  Yoshito Sengok  will hold a media briefing at 4 p.m.  
 The yield on the 1.225 percent government bond due June
2020 was 1.22 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest inter-dealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 90.93 per dollar at 7:22 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: The finance ministry will auction 28 billion yuan
($4.1 billion) of 30-year bonds at 4.015 percent today,
according to a Bloomberg News survey. The ministry will also
auction 28.6 billion yuan of three-year bonds and 15.2 billion
yuan of five-year debt.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due May 2020 was 3.32
percent, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. The yuan was
at 6.8296 per dollar.  
 India: The government plans to raise as much as 110 billion
rupees ($2.4 billion) by selling bonds maturing in 2012 and
2022.  
 The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.64
percent. The rupee was at 46.31.  
 Malaysia: A government report today will show consumer
prices rose last month at the fastest pace in a year, according
to a Bloomberg survey. Economists forecast an inflation rate of
1.6 percent, compared with 1.5 percent in April.  
 The yield on the 4.378 percent note due November 2019 was
4.04 percent. The ringgit was at 3.2595.  
 South Korea: Spending at the nation’s three biggest chains
climbed 8 percent in May from a year earlier, after rising an
annual 8.8 percent in April, according to a Ministry of
Knowledge Economy report today.  
 The yield on South Korea’s 4.5 percent bond due in March
2015 was 4.40 percent. The won was at 1,213.60.  
